<|startoftext|>Question:what is the difference between an IP address and a domain and what is the difference between the domain and the domain
Answer:For a domain you are using TCP/IP and a domain you are using Internet Connection Sharing (a peer over IP). IP address is the information that every packet has from the IP address, domain, hostname, port 001; the packet will go over that IP address so that only the IP-listening IP(R) can get out from a packet. The IP-listener has to have the TCP/IP packet for the routing range that is in their IP (and not in the domain itself). They can only receive packets over the IP address. For the domain it just goes around the network and the IP-listener gets a ""local address"" and sets the local address so that only the locals on the network will know the IP-listeners IP range.<|endoftext|>
